p
    h1 Attributes example
    span Tag attributes look similar to html, however their values are just regular JavaScript.
    div
        a(href='google.com') Google
    div
        a(class='button', href='google.com') Google
p
    span All the normal JavaScript expressions work fine too:
    - var isButton = true
    div
        a(class=isButton ? 'button' : '', href='google.com') Google

p
    span If you have many attributes, you can also spread them across many lines:
    div
        input(
            type='checkbox'
            name='agreement'
            checked
        )

p
    h2 Boolean Attributes
    span Boolean attributes are mirrored by Jade, and accept bools, aka true or false. When no value is specified true is assumed.
    div
        input(type='checkbox', checked)
        input(type='checkbox', checked=true)
        input(type='checkbox', checked=false)
        input(type='checkbox', checked=true.toString())
p
    h2 Style Attributes
    span style attribute can be a string (like any normal attribute) but it can also be an object, which is handy when parts of the style are generated by JavaScript.
    div
        a(style={color: 'red', background: 'green'})

p
    h2 Class Attributes
    span The class attribute can be a string (like any normal attribute) but it can also be an array of class names, which is handy when generated from JavaScript.
    - var classes = ['foo', 'bar', 'baz']
    div
        a(class=classes) classes

p
    span the class attribute may also be repeated to merge arrays
    div
        a.initCls(class=classes class=['bing']) merged classes

p
    span It can also be an object mapping class names to true or false values, which is useful for applying conditional classes
    div
        - var currentUrl = '/about'
        a(class={active: currentUrl === '/'} href='/') Home
        a(class={active: currentUrl === '/about'} href='/about') About

